Rice Farmers In Biniwe Expect Early Harvest This Season - Leadership Hausa Newspapers.
Rice farmers in Biniwe State are expecting a bumper harvest about two months after planting.
Some of them who were interviewed in Makurdi expressed hope that the harvest would be anytime between October and November.
A small farmer in Mbatiab-Gboko town of the state, Titus Atondo, said that he planted his rice in an area of two hectares in July.
Atondo said he got the seeds from the market in his area and they are in two groups of CP and OC rice while he uses Dazzle to clear the land for planting and fertilizing.
According to Titus Atondo, the challenges of rice farming in rural areas such as Maina are many because we rely heavily on labor as customers cannot access the farm.
Titus Atondo added that we are hiring people who will work in the farm from the ground level to harvest, where he added that this is tiring and too much.
Atondo said that the total expenditure on his farm which is currently in place including planting, weeding, application of fertilizers and expected harvest is N2020,000.
Titus Atondo continued to say, however, he expects at least 50 sacks as harvest from the two acres which will probably be sold at the price of 29,000 Naira per 100k sack.
Another big rice farmer, Bitalis Tarnongu, planted in June to July in 274 hectares of the farm where the price stood at 14,500 Naira per hectare while the land paid 25,000 Naira per hectare.
He planted 44 seeds (Supi) and Faro 61 (OC) seeds obtained from the National Council of Crops (seeds) and some originated from Olam Nigeria.
He added that the levels of growth at this time are in different areas while some are in the breeding program, and some are in the first stage of slaughtering animals as the farm was cultivated in stages.
Tarnongu added that the challenges so far include financial ones since the cost of producing selected animals is expensive and the cost of labor has increased.
He said the harvest is expected to start in October to November.
He added that the total price of raw materials at the end of the day will be a minimum of 246,000 Naira per hectare while the production of three tons of honey is expected which can translate to 360,000 Naira at a cost of 120 Naira per kilo.
Tarnongu does not use pesticides on his rice farm, instead, he advises and implements traditional farming practices, adding that, therefore, we use highly effective insecticides, insecticides and chemical fertilizer.
The Chairman of the National Association of Farmers (AFAN) Benue state branch, Comrade Aondongu Saaku, expressed hope that the rainy season this year will be suitable for the production of large amounts of rice.
