2,732 people were murdered between April and June in Nigeria - Report
It is estimated that 2,732 people were killed in Nigeria in just two months, from April to June.
The report which was issued by an institution called SBM intelligence in Lagos, said that it collected the information from the reports published by various newspapers in this country.
The report gathered statistics from newspapers on the number of killings, including killings by Boko Haram, killings by kidnappers, bandit attacks, herdsmen attacks and killings related to tribal and rural areas.
This major statistical project is a collaboration between SBM Intelligence and an organization called &quot;Enough is Enough&quot;.
In April, the SBM published an estimate of the killings of about 1,000 people, which it said were the number of those reported by newspapers to have been killed between January and March, 2020.
SBM said that the report includes evidence from security studies, monitoring organizations on the impact of external and internal security problems.
And she listed all the names of the groups.
The killing of those who did not hear and did not see became more serious due to the lack of concentration of the government and the security forces in trying to stop the killings.
The report also mentions how the confinement of people at home due to the Corona virus has led to poverty and unemployment for young people estimated at 43%.
One of the security analysts at SBM Intelligence, named Confidence Isaiah, explained some of the reasons behind the increase in killings from April to June.
Isaiah said that Boko Haram has killed soldiers, and the bandits have changed from stealing cattle and kidnapping people to using their weapons of choice to kill people.
They reported the killings in 33 states and Abuja, including the killing of 221 security personnel including 173 soldiers, 39 policemen, 3 NSCDC, all in three months.
They also said that 845 terrorists and 502 gunmen were killed.
941 people were killed in Barno, 143 in Yobe, Taraba 113, Zamfara 444, Katsina 207, Sokoto 99, Kaduna 179.
